ves and the nouns they modify, or between a final adjective and the noun in a list.\r\n\r\n**Correct Examples:**\r\n* The talented musician performed beautifully.\r\n* She bought new, comfortable shoes.\r\n\r\n**Incorrect Examples:**\r\n* The talented, musician performed beautifully.\r\n* She bought new, comfortable, shoes.\r\n\r\n## F. Between Subjects and Verbs\r\nDo not place a comma between the subject and the verb of a sentence unless it's separated by a non-essential clause.\r\n\r\n**Correct Examples:**\r\n* The manager, who is very experienced, approved the budget.\r\n* My brother, who lives in New York, visited us.\r\n\r\n**Incorrect Examples:**\r\n* The manager, approved the budget.\r\n* My brother, visited us.\r\n\r\n## G. Between Compound Elements\r\nWhen combining two independent clauses with a coordinating conjunction (for, and, nor, but, or, yet, so), use a comma before the conjunction.\r\n\r\n**Correct Examples:**\r\n* We wanted to go to the beach, but it started raining.\r\n* She studied hard, so she passed the exam.\r\n\r\n**Incorrect Examples:**\r\n* We wanted to go to the beach but it started raining.\r\n* She studied hard so she passed the exam.\r\n\r\n## H. Before or Around "Self" Words\r\nDo not place a comma before or after reflexive pronouns (myself, yourself, himself, herself, itself, ourselves, yourselves, themselves).\r\n\r\n**Correct Examples:**\r\n* He made the decision himself.\r\n* She prepared the presentation herself.\r\n\r\n**Incorrect Examples:**\r\n* He made the decision, himself.\r\n* She prepared the presentation, herself.\r\n\r\nBy understanding and correctly applying these rules, you can ensure your writing is clear, effective, and grammatically correct.	\N
