62	11	punctuation-4	Colons and Dashes		Study Guide: Colons and Dashes\r\nColons\r\nUsage of Colons\r\nColons should be used in two main situations:\r\n1.\tBefore a list: When introducing a list, a colon should be used after a complete sentence.\r\n2.\tBefore an explanation: When providing an explanation or elaboration after a complete sentence.\r\nImportant: The information before a colon must be a complete sentence, but the information after can be a sentence or a fragment.\r\nExamples\r\n1. Before a List\r\n•\tIncorrect: The artist's favorite mediums include: oils, watercolors, and pastels.\r\n•\tCorrect: The artist's favorite mediums include oils, watercolors, and pastels.\r\n•\tIncorrect: The picnic basket had: sandwiches, fruits, drinks, and desserts.\r\n•\tCorrect: The picnic basket had sandwiches, fruits, drinks, and desserts.\r\n2. Before an Explanation\r\n•\tIncorrect: The reason for the delay is: the train was late.\r\n•\tCorrect: The reason for the delay is simple: the train was late.\r\n•\tIncorrect: The solution is: to increase the budget.\r\n•\tCorrect: The solution is clear: increase the budget.\r\nDashes\r\nUsage of Dashes\r\nDashes have three primary uses:\r\n1.\tSet off non-essential clauses: Two dashes can be used to add non-essential information in a sentence.\r\n2.\tIntroduce a list or explanation: A dash can serve the same function as a colon.\r\n3.\tCreate a deliberate pause: Dashes can be used for emphasis or to create a dramatic pause.\r\nExamples\r\n1. Set off Non-Essential Clauses\r\n•\tIncorrect: My brother who lives in New York is visiting us next week.\r\n•\tCorrect: My brother—who lives in New York—is visiting us next week.\r\n•\tIncorrect: The CEO who is known for her innovative strategies will speak at the conference.\r\n•\tCorrect: The CEO—who is known for her innovative strategies—will speak at the conference.\r\n2. Introduce a List or Explanation\r\n•\tIncorrect: Her response was clear: yes.\r\n•\tCorrect: Her response was clear—y