71	14	agreement-tense	Verbs: Agreement and Tense		The SAT contains two types of verb questions:\r\n1.\tSubject-verb agreement\r\n2.\tVerb tense\r\nAlthough some questions may test both concepts, it is important to understand that they are distinct.\r\n•\tAgreement answers the question "singular or plural?" Verbs must agree with their subjects: singular subjects must take singular verbs, and plural subjects must take plural verbs.\r\n•\tTense answers the question "when?" It indicates past, present, or future.\r\nSubject-Verb Agreement\r\nSubject-verb agreement errors occur when the verb does not correctly match the subject in number.\r\nExample:\r\n•\tIncorrect: The sound of the waves soothe me.\r\n•\tCorrect: The sound of the waves soothes me.\r\nIn the incorrect example, "sound" is a singular noun, but "soothe" is a plural verb. The correct form uses the singular verb "soothes."\r\nTips for Identifying Subject-Verb Agreement Errors\r\n1.\tLook at the answer choices. If you examine the answer choices, you can determine if the question is testing subject-verb agreement. Answer choices that mix singular and plural forms indicate a subject-verb agreement question.\r\n2.\tIdentify the subject, and determine whether it is singular or plural. Remember that the noun right before a verb usually won’t be the subject. Look for the main subject of the sentence, which might be at the beginning.\r\n3.\tFind the verb that agrees with the subject. Singular subjects require singular verbs, and plural subjects require plural verbs.\r\nExample:\r\n•\tThe paintings by Vincent van Gogh (1) captivate audiences worldwide.\r\no\tA) NO CHANGE\r\no\tB) captivates\r\no\tC) captivated\r\no\tD) captivating\r\nHere, "paintings" is plural, so the correct verb form is "captivate" (A).\r\nSubject-Verb Agreement with Non-Essential Clauses\r\nNon-essential clauses can distract from the subject-verb agreement by inserting extra information between the subject and the verb.\r\nExample:\r\n•\tIncorrect: The trees, which are more than a hundred years old, needs to be trimmed.\r\n•\tCorrect: The trees, which are more than a hundred years old, need to be trimmed.\r\nHere, "trees" is the plural subject, and it requires the plural verb "need."\r\nPrepositional Phrases\r\nPrepositional phrases often appear between the subject and the verb, potentially causing confusion.\r\nExample:\r\n•\tIncorrect: The bouquet of roses were given to the bride.\r\n•\tCorrect: The bouquet of roses was given to the bride.\r\nHere, "bouquet" is the singular subject, and it requires the singular verb "was."\r\nVerb Tense\r\nVerb tense errors occur when the verb tense does not correctly indicate the time of the action.\r\nExample:\r\n•\tIncorrect: Yesterday, she write a letter to her grandmother.\r\n•\tCorrect: Yesterday, she wrote a letter to her grandmother.\r\nIn the correct example, "wrote" is the past tense form that matches the time indicator "yesterday."\r\nPractice Questions\r\n1.\tThe manager (1) say that the project will be completed by the end of the week.\r\no\tA) NO CHANGE\r\no\tB) said\r\no\tC) says\r\no\tD) saying\r\n2.\tThe committee members (2) meets every Wednesday to discuss the project.\r\no\tA) NO CHANGE\r\no\tB) meet\r\no\tC) meeting\r\no\tD) to meet\r\n3.\tThe book, which (3) contains detailed illustrations and photographs, are an excellent resource for students.\r\no\tA) NO CHANGE\r\no\tB) is\r\no\tC) was\r\no\tD) will be\r\n4.\tThe teacher (4) explains the concept to the students every Monday.\r\no\tA) NO CHANGE\r\no\tB) explained\r\no\tC) explaining\r\no\tD) will explain\r\n5.\tThe flowers in the garden (5) blooms beautifully every spring.\r\no\tA) NO CHANGE\r\no\tB) bloom\r\no\tC) blooming\r\no\tD) bloomed\r\nAdditional Unique Examples:\r\nSubject-Verb Agreement with Compound Subjects\r\nExample:\r\n•\tIncorrect: The dog and the cat loves to play in the yard.\r\n•\tCorrect: The dog and the cat love to play in the yard.\r\nHere, "dog and the cat" is a compound subject, and it requires the plural verb "love."\r\nSubject-Verb Agreement with Collective Nouns\r\nExample:\r\n•\tIncorrect: The team is winning their games.\r\n•\tCorrect: The team is winning its games.\r\nHere, "team" is a collective noun that is treated as singular, requiring the singular possessive "its."\r\nSubject-Verb Agreement with Inverted Sentences\r\nExample:\r\n•\tIncorrect: There is many reasons to celebrate.\r\n•\tCorrect: There are many reasons to celebrate.\r\nHere, "reasons" is a plural subject, and it requires the plural verb "are."\r\nVerb Tense Consistency\r\nExample:\r\n•\tIncorrect: She starts to run and then tripped over a rock.\r\n•\tCorrect: She started to run and then tripped over a rock.\r\nHere, the actions are in the past, so the past tense "started" and "tripped" are used.	\N
72	14	pronoun-noun	Pronoun and Noun Agreement		Introduction\r\nPronoun and noun agreement is a critical aspect of English grammar, particularly in standardized tests like the SAT. Ensuring that pronouns match their antecedents in both number and gender is essential for clarity and precision in writing.\r\nSingular and Plural Pronouns\r\nA pronoun must agree with its antecedent (the noun it refers to) in number and gender.\r\n•\tSingular: Each student must bring his or her notebook.\r\n•\tPlural: All students must bring their notebooks.\r\nExamples:\r\n•\tIncorrect: If a student wants to succeed, they must study hard.\r\no\tCorrect: If a student wants to succeed, he or she must study hard.\r\n•\tIncorrect: The teachers were discussing his new curriculum.\r\no\tCorrect: The teachers were discussing their new curriculum.\r\nTypes of Pronouns\r\n1.\tPersonal Pronouns:\r\no\tSingular: he, she, it, his, her, its\r\no\tPlural: they, them, their\r\n2.\tIndefinite Pronouns:\r\no\tSingular: anyone, everyone, each, either, neither\r\no\tPlural: few, many, several, both\r\no\tVariable: some, all, most (depends on the context)\r\nExamples:\r\n•\tIncorrect: Someone left their umbrella in the hallway.\r\no\tCorrect: Someone left his or her umbrella in the hallway.\r\n•\tIncorrect: Each of the players has their own locker.\r\no\tCorrect: Each of the players has his or her own locker.\r\nCommon Errors\r\n1.\tMismatch in Number:\r\no\tIncorrect: Each of the boys brought their book.\r\no\tCorrect: Each of the boys brought his book.\r\n2.\tAmbiguous Antecedent:\r\no\tIncorrect: When Jessica and Maria went to the store, she bought some ice cream. (Who is 'she'?)\r\no\tCorrect: When Jessica and Maria went to the store, Jessica bought some ice cream.\r\nPronouns with Collective Nouns\r\nCollective nouns can be singular or plural based on the context.\r\n•\tSingular: The jury has reached its decision.\r\n•\tPlural: The jury have argued among themselves.\r\nExamples:\r\n•\tIncorrect: The team won its match and celebrated their victory.\r\no\tCorrect: The team won its match and celebrated its victory.\r\n•\tIncorrect: The jury has reached their verdict.\r\no\tCorrect: The jury has reached its verdict.\r\nEmphatic Pronouns\r\n"Self" words like myself, yourself, himself, herself, itself, ourselves, yourselves, themselves are used for emphasis.\r\n•\tIncorrect: The author discusses the book itself.\r\n•\tCorrect: The author discusses the book itself.\r\nMissing or Ambiguous Antecedent\r\nWhen a pronoun refers to a noun that is missing or unclear, the sentence can be confusing.\r\n•\tIncorrect: Alex told Jordan that he would win the prize. (Who is 'he'?)\r\no\tCorrect: Alex told Jordan, "You will win the prize."\r\nExamples:\r\n•\tIncorrect: When the car hit the tree, it was damaged.\r\no\tCorrect: When the car hit the tree, the car was damaged.\r\n•\tIncorrect: The teacher told the student that he would win the prize. (Who is 'he'?)\r\no\tCorrect: The teacher told the student that the student would win the prize.\r\nPractice Questions\r\nQuestion 1\r\nEach of the boys must bring his own lunch.\r\n•\tA) NO CHANGE\r\n•\tB) their\r\n•\tC) they're\r\n•\tD) its\r\nCorrect Answer: A\r\nQuestion 2\r\nThe committee has finished its report.\r\n•\tA) NO CHANGE\r\n•\tB) their\r\n•\tC) it's\r\n•\tD) they're\r\nCorrect Answer: A\r\nQuestion 3\r\nIf anyone calls, tell him or her to wait.\r\n•\tA) NO CHANGE\r\n•\tB) them\r\n•\tC) their\r\n•\tD) it's\r\nCorrect Answer: A\r\nQuestion 4\r\nThe teacher and the student discussed their project.\r\n•\tA) NO CHANGE\r\n•\tB) his\r\n•\tC) her\r\n•\tD) it's\r\nCorrect Answer: A\r\nQuestion 5\r\nSomeone forgot to take his or her coat.\r\n•\tA) NO CHANGE\r\n•\tB) their\r\n•\tC) they're\r\n•\tD) its\r\nCorrect Answer: A\r\nSingular vs. Plural Pronouns in Context\r\n•\tIncorrect: If a student wants to succeed, they must study hard.\r\no\tCorrect: If a student wants to succeed, he or she must study hard.\r\n•\tIncorrect: The teachers were discussing his new curriculum.\r\no\tCorrect: The teachers were discussing their new curriculum.\r\nPronouns with Collective Nouns\r\n•\tIncorrect: The team won its match and celebrated their victory.\r\no\tCorrect: The team won its match and celebrated its victory.\r\n•\tIncorrect: The jury has reached their verdict.\r\no\tCorrect: The jury has reached its verdict.\r\nPronouns with Indefinite Antecedents\r\n•\tIncorrect: Someone left their umbrella in the hallway.\r\no\tCorrect: Someone left his or her umbrella in the hallway.\r\n•\tIncorrect: Each of the players has their own locker.\r\no\tCorrect: Each of the players has his or her own locker.\r\nAvoiding Ambiguity\r\n•\tIncorrect: When the car hit the tree, it was damaged.\r\no\tCorrect: When the car hit the tree, the car was damaged.\r\n•\tIncorrect: The teacher told the student that he would win the prize. (Who is 'he'?)\r\no\tCorrect: The teacher told the student that the student would win the prize.\r\nPractice Questions (Indexed from 1)\r\nQuestion 1\r\nEach of the boys must bring his own lunch.\r\n•\tA) NO CHANGE\r\n•\tB) their\r\n•\tC) they're\r\n•\tD) its\r\nCorrect Answer: A\r\nQuestion 2\r\nThe committee has finished its report.\r\n•\tA) NO CHANGE\r\n•\tB) their\r\n•\tC) it's\r\n•\tD) they're\r\nCorrect Answer: A\r\nQuestion 3\r\nIf anyone calls, tell him or her to wait.\r\n•\tA) NO CHANGE\r\n•\tB) them\r\n•\tC) their\r\n•\tD) it's\r\nCorrect Answer: A\r\nQuestion 4\r\nThe teacher and the student discussed their project.\r\n•\tA) NO CHANGE\r\n•\tB) his\r\n•\tC) her\r\n•\tD) it's\r\nCorrect Answer: A\r\nQuestion 5\r\nSomeone forgot to take his or her coat.\r\n•\tA) NO CHANGE\r\n•\tB) their\r\n•\tC) they're\r\n•\tD) its\r\nCorrect Answer: A	\N
73	14	word-pairs-comparison	Word Pairs and Comparisons		Word Pairs\r\nWord pairs help indicate similarity or difference. Here are some common word pairs and examples of their use:\r\nA. As...as\r\n•\tIncorrect: The library is as quiet than the museum.\r\n•\tCorrect: The library is as quiet as the museum.\r\nB. Not only...but (also)\r\n•\tIncorrect: She is not only a doctor and a researcher.\r\n•\tCorrect: She is not only a doctor but also a researcher.\r\nC. More/–ER...than, Less...than\r\n•\tIncorrect: This novel is more interesting as the previous one.\r\n•\tCorrect: This novel is more interesting than the previous one.\r\nD. (N)either...(n)or\r\n•\tIncorrect: Neither the dog or the cat was seen in the yard.\r\n•\tCorrect: Neither the dog nor the cat was seen in the yard.\r\nFaulty Comparisons\r\nFaulty comparisons occur when the items being compared are not comparable.\r\nSingular Faulty Comparison\r\n•\tIncorrect: The taste of this coffee is better than any tea.\r\n•\tCorrect: The taste of this coffee is better than that of any tea.\r\nPlural Faulty Comparison\r\n•\tIncorrect: The sculptures in this gallery are more intriguing than the museum.\r\n•\tCorrect: The sculptures in this gallery are more intriguing than those in the museum.\r\nComparing Amounts: Fewer vs. Less, Many vs. Much\r\nFewer and many are used for countable items, whereas less and much are used for uncountable items.\r\nFewer vs. Less\r\n•\tIncorrect: There are less trees in the park now.\r\n•\tCorrect: There are fewer trees in the park now.\r\nMany vs. Much\r\n•\tIncorrect: There is much cars in the parking lot.\r\n•\tCorrect: There are many cars in the parking lot.\r\nPractice Questions\r\n1.\tIn recent years, urban development has led to significant changes in city landscapes, and no city has experienced as much transformation 1 as New York City. The introduction of modern architectural designs has not only altered the skyline 2 but also changed the way people interact with urban spaces.\r\n