75	14	relative-prouns	Relative Pronouns		Relative pronouns are essential for connecting clauses and providing additional information about a noun in a sentence. Understanding their correct usage is crucial for effective writing and SAT performance.\r\nKey Relative Pronouns\r\n•\tWho: Refers to people.\r\n•\tWhom: Refers to people, used as an object of a verb or preposition.\r\n•\tWhose: Shows possession for people or things.\r\n•\tWhich: Refers to things or animals, used for non-essential clauses.\r\n•\tThat: Refers to people, things, or animals, used for essential clauses.\r\nUsing Relative Pronouns\r\n1.\tWho vs. Whom\r\no\tWho is used as a subject:\r\n\tThe scientist who discovered the cure won the Nobel Prize.\r\no\tWhom is used as an object:\r\n\tThe candidate whom the committee selected was well-qualified.\r\n2.\tWhose\r\no\tIndicates possession:\r\n\tThe writer whose book you read is giving a lecture.\r\n3.\tWhich vs. That\r\no\tWhich is used for non-essential (non-restrictive) clauses, and is usually set off by commas:\r\n\tThe car, which was red, sped past us.\r\no\tThat is used for essential (restrictive) clauses, and is not set off by commas:\r\n\tThe car that is red sped past us.\r\nCommon Errors and Corrections\r\n1.\tIncorrect: The dog, that barked loudly, scared the mailman.\r\no\tCorrect: The dog, which barked loudly, scared the mailman.\r\no\tExplanation: Use "which" for non-essential clauses.\r\n2.\tIncorrect: The teacher who she admired most was retiring.\r\no\tCorrect: The teacher whom she admired most was retiring.\r\no\tExplanation: Use "whom" as the object of "admired."\r\n3.\tIncorrect: The book whose cover is torn belongs to the library.\r\no\tCorrect: The book whose cover is torn belongs to the library.\r\no\tExplanation: "Whose" is correctly used for possession.\r\nPractice Questions\r\n1.\tThe biography of Marie Curie, (who/whom) discovered radium and polonium, is both inspiring and educational.\r\n2.\tThe novel, (which/that) is set during World War II, explores themes of bravery and sacrifice.\r\n3.\tThe artist (whose/whom) paintings were featured in the gallery is renowned worldwide.\r\n4.\tThe recipe, (that/which) calls for exotic spices, is a family secret passed down through generations.\r\n5.\tThe engineers (who/whom) developed the new technology were awarded a prestigious prize.\r\nAnswers and Explanations\r\n1.\tWho\r\no\tExplanation: "Who" is the subject of the verb "discovered."\r\n2.\tWhich\r\no\tExplanation: "Which" is used for the non-essential clause describing the novel.\r\n3.\tWhose\r\no\tExplanation: "Whose" indicates possession of the paintings.\r\n4.\tWhich\r\no\tExplanation: "Which" is used for the non-essential clause describing the recipe.\r\n5.\tWho\r\no\tExplanation: "Who" is the subject of the verb "developed."\r\nTips for Success\r\n•\tAlways identify whether the clause is essential or non-essential.\r\n•\tDetermine if the pronoun is used as a subject or an object in the sentence.\r\n•\tPay attention to the context to choose the appropriate relative pronoun.\r\nBy mastering the use of relative pronouns, you can enhance the clarity and precision of your writing, an essential skill for the SAT and effective communication in general.\r\nPractice Questions: Relative Pronouns\r\nQuestion 1\r\nThe ancient ruins of Machu Picchu, ____ attract millions of tourists each year, are a testament to the architectural prowess of the Inca civilization. Nestled high in the Andes Mountains of Peru, these ruins are a UNESCO World Heritage site. Researchers continue to uncover new aspects of the city whose precise original purpose remains a subject of debate among historians.\r\nA) which\r\nB) that\r\nC) whom\r\nD) who\r\nCorrect Answer: A) which\r\nExplanation: "Which" is used for non-essential clauses referring to things.\r\nQuestion 2\r\nThe autobiography of Frederick Douglass, ____ was a former slave and a prominent abolitionist, provides a vivid account of his life and the brutal realities of slavery in the 19th century. His eloquent writing and powerful speeches played a crucial role in the fight for freedom and equality. The book, which has been widely read and studied, remains an important work in American literature and history.\r\nA) who\r\nB) whom\r\nC) that\r\nD) whose\r\nCorrect Answer: A) who\r\nExplanation: "Who" is used for people.\r\nQuestion 3\r\nJane Goodall's groundbreaking research on chimpanzees, ____ she observed in the wild for over five decades, has significantly advanced our understanding of primate behavior and social structures. Her detailed notes and observations challenged previous notions about the similarities between humans and our closest relatives. Goodall's work, which continues to inspire new generations of scientists and conservationists, highlights the importance of preserving natural habitats.\r\nA) who\r\nB) whom\r\nC) whose\r\nD) that\r\nCorrect Answer: B) whom\r\nExplanation: "Whom" is used for people and follows a preposition (in this case, "on").\r\nQuestion 4\r\nThe novel "To Kill a Mockingbird" by Harper Lee, ____ explores themes of racial injustice and moral growth, is set in the fictional town of Maycomb, Alabama, during the 1930s. The story is told through the eyes of Scout Finch, a young girl whose father, Atticus Finch, is an attorney defending a black man falsely accused of raping a white woman. The novel's enduring impact is reflected in the numerous awards and recognitions it has received over the years.\r\nA) which\r\nB) who\r\nC) whom\r\nD) that\r\nCorrect Answer: A) which\r\nExplanation: "Which" is used for non-essential clauses referring to things.\r\nQuestion 5\r\nThe first successful ascent of Mount Everest, ____ was achieved by Sir Edmund Hillary and Tenzing Norgay in 1953, marked a significant milestone in the history of mountaineering. This remarkable feat demonstrated human endurance and the drive to conquer the world's highest peaks. Today, the routes established by these pioneering climbers are still used by adventurers from around the globe who seek to reach the summit of this iconic mountain.\r\nA) which\r\nB) whom\r\nC) whose\r\nD) that\r\nCorrect Answer: D) that\r\nExplanation: "That" is used for essential clauses referring to things, and no comma is used before "that."\r\nQuestion 1\r\nThe research paper on climate change, ____ has been widely cited in academic circles, presents compelling evidence on the rapid melting of polar ice caps. The authors, who are renowned scientists, emphasize the urgent need for global action to mitigate the effects of climate change.\r\nA) which\r\nB) who\r\nC) whom\r\nD) that\r\nCorrect Answer: A) which\r\nExplanation: "Which" is used for non-essential clauses referring to things.\r\nQuestion 2\r\nThe artist ____ painting sold for a record-breaking price at the auction is known for his innovative use of color and form. His work, which has been exhibited in galleries worldwide, continues to inspire new generations of artists.\r\nA) who\r\nB) whose\r\nC) whom\r\nD) that\r\nCorrect Answer: B) whose\r\nExplanation: "Whose" is the possessive form and is used to show ownership by the artist.\r\nQuestion 3\r\nThe conference on renewable energy, ____ was attended by over 500 delegates from around the world, highlighted the latest advancements in solar and wind technologies. The keynote speaker, who is a leading expert in the field, discussed the future of sustainable energy solutions.\r\nA) who\r\nB) whom\r\nC) whose\r\nD) which\r\nCorrect Answer: D) which\r\nExplanation: "Which" is used for non-essential clauses referring to things.\r\nQuestion 4\r\nThe historical documentary, ____ covers the rise and fall of ancient civilizations, offers a fascinating glimpse into the past. It includes interviews with historians and archaeologists whose research has shed light on these long-lost cultures.\r\nA) who\r\nB) which\r\nC) whom\r\nD) that\r\nCorrect Answer: B) which\r\nExplanation: "Which" is used for non-essential clauses referring to things.\r\nQuestion 5\r\nThe philanthropist, ____ donations have funded numerous educational programs, was honored at the gala event. Her generosity, which has made a significant impact on many lives, was celebrated by all in attendance.\r\nA) who\r\nB) whose\r\nC) whom\r\nD) that\r\nCorrect Answer: B) whose\r\nExplanation: "Whose" is the possessive form and is used to show ownership by the philanthropist.	\N
